title: ABL Space Systems joining smallsat launch market with growing number of contracts
summary: Another smallsat launch provider is looking to debut in 2021, entering a busy market of new commercial rockets. Among the many new companies proposing to provide dedicated launches for small satellites, ABL Space Systems has accumulated several launch contracts which position the company well for a first launch this year.

title: Media Invited to NASA’s Laser Communications Demonstration Launch
summary: U.S. media accreditation has opened for an upcoming rocket launch with a NASA payload that aims to enhance communications capabilities for the agency’s future missions, including the potential to increase bandwidth 10 to 100 times more than radio frequency systems.

title: NASA Invites Media to Launch of Boeing’s Orbital Flight Test-2
summary: Media accreditation is open for prelaunch and launch activities for NASA’s Boeing Orbital Flight Test-2 (OFT-2) mission to the International Space Station, the second uncrewed flight test of the company’s CST-100 Starliner spacecraft for NASA’s Commercial Crew Program.

title: Pennsylvania, Texas Students to Hear from Astronauts on Space Station
summary: Pennsylvania and Texas students have opportunities next week to hear from astronauts aboard the International Space Station.

title: Starfish Space testing software for constellation-managing Otter space tugs
summary: Starfish Space, a startup founded by former Blue Origin and NASA engineers, is developing space tugs to help manage rapidly growing megaconstellations.

title: United Launch Alliance nears first fueling test on Vulcan rocket
summary: United Launch Alliance could load cryogenic methane and liquid oxygen propellants into a Vulcan rocket test article at Cape Canaveral for the first time in the coming weeks, timing key tests for the next-generation rocket in between flights of Atlas 5 rockets that will share the same launch complex for the next few years.

title: ESA awards study contracts for lunar communications and navigation systems
summary: The European Space Agency has issued contracts to two European industry groups to begin concept studies of lunar satellite systems that would provide communications and navigation services.

title: Rocket Report: A new space race in India, Elon’s hat is safe for now
summary: "This is not the time to cut corners on environmental review."

title: NASA Invites Media to Briefing on Science Launching to Space Station
summary: NASA will host a media teleconference at 1 p.m. EDT Wednesday, May 26, to discuss select science investigations launching on the next SpaceX commercial resupply flight to the International Space Station.

title: Firefly selects SpaceX to launch its lunar lander
summary: Firefly Aerospace announced May 20 it selected SpaceX to launch its first lunar lander mission for NASA, the latest in a series of contract wins by SpaceX for lunar missions.

title: NASA, ESA, JAXA Host Hackathon to Study COVID-19’s Environmental Effects
summary: The measures countries have taken in response to COVID-19, ranging from large-scale lockdowns to the mass deployment of personal protective equipment, have resulted in environmental effects.

title: With ULA’s new rocket Vulcan behind schedule, Space Force agrees to let Atlas 5 fill in
summary: What would have been the first national security mission for United Launch Alliance’s Vulcan Centaur rocket will be flown by Atlas 5, the company confirmed May 19.

title: Europe making progress on sovereign LEO constellation as OneWeb and Starlink race ahead
summary: The industry consortium devising a satellite network to keep the European Union from falling too far behind the megaconstellation goldrush is weeks away from nailing down key criteria.

title: China scrubs second launch attempt of Tianzhou 2, first cargo launch to new station
summary: China has scrubbed the second launch attempt in as many days of its Tianzhou 2 cargo mission to its new space station. Liftoff was expected Thursday, 20 May at 17:09 UTC / 13:09 EDT aboard a Chang Zheng 7 rocket. Wednesday’s launch attempt (UTC) was also scrubbed due a reported technical issue.

title: Salts Could Be Important Piece of Martian Organic Puzzle
summary: A NASA team has found that organic, or carbon-containing, salts are likely present on Mars, with implications for the Red Planet's past habitability.

title: SLS Core Stage thermal protection system refurbishment in work at Kennedy for Artemis 1
summary: NASA’s Space Launch System (SLS) and Exploration Ground Systems (EGS) programs are working with Core Stage prime contractor Boeing and prime test operations and support contractor Jacobs to finish repairs to thermal protection system (TPS) spray-on foam insulation on the Artemis 1 Core Stage at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

title: Virgin Galactic schedules next SpaceShipTwo test flight for May 22
summary: Virgin Galactic will attempt its next SpaceShipTwo suborbital test flight as soon as May 22 after resolving concerns about the maintenance of its carrier aircraft.
